    "body": "To anyone looking for the answer, here is how you verify proxy contracts on etherscan using hardhat manually. Replace the values show in <> with your own (without the <>).\r\n\r\n1. Verify your proxy contract and it's implementation normally first.  \r\n```\r\nnpx hardhat verify --network rinkeby <Address of contract>\r\n```\r\n2. Run the following fetch request,\r\n```\r\nvar formdata = new FormData();\r\nformdata.append(\"address\", \"<Address of the Verified Proxy Contract>\");\r\nformdata.append(\"expectedimplementation\", \"<Address of the Verified Implementation Contract>\");\r\n\r\nvar requestOptions = {\r\n  method: 'POST',\r\n  body: formdata,\r\n  redirect: 'follow'\r\n};\r\n\r\nfetch(\"https://api-rinkeby.etherscan.io/api?module=contract&action=verifyproxycontract&apikey=<Etherscan APIKEY>\", requestOptions)\r\n  .then(response => response.text())\r\n  .then(result => console.log(result))\r\n  .catch(error => console.log('error', error));\r\n```\r\n3. The response will contain a `guid` that you can use to follow the result of the verification like this,\r\n```\r\nvar requestOptions = {\r\n  method: 'GET',\r\n  redirect: 'follow'\r\n};\r\n\r\nfetch(\"https://api.etherscan.io/api?module=contract&action=checkproxyverification&guid=<Your GUID>&apikey=<Etherscan APIKEY>\", requestOptions)\r\n  .then(response => response.text())\r\n  .then(result => console.log(result))\r\n  .catch(error => console.log('error', error));\r\n```\r\n\r\nThis should now let you Read/Write as a proxy in Etherscan.",
